('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:exam:a298608c', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q1", "question": "<p>Tick <strong>one</strong> box to identify which of these is a <strong>high-level</strong> language.</p>", "options": ["Machine code", "Python", "Binary", "Assembly language"], "hint": "Which of these uses English-like keywords, rather than binary or mnemonics?"}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<ul><li><strong>Python</strong></li></ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>How the marks are given</h5>\n<ul><li>Only the correct option scores; 2 or more ticks scores 0.</li></ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": "Python."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:exam:c109de5d', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q2", "question": "<p>Tick <strong>one</strong> box to identify the only language a CPU can execute directly.</p>", "options": ["Assembly language", "Machine code", "A high-level language", "Pseudocode"], "hint": "Which of these is written entirely in binary?"}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<ul><li><strong>Machine code</strong></li></ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": "Machine code."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:exam:0d36c74f', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q10", "question": "<p>Tick <strong>one</strong> box to identify a short abbreviation, such as <strong>ADD</strong> or <strong>LDA</strong>, used in assembly language.</p>", "options": ["A translator", "A mnemonic", "An executable file", "A constant"], "hint": "This term describes the short, memorable instruction words themselves."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark</h5>\n<ul><li><strong>A mnemonic</strong></li></ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": "A mnemonic."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:mcq:78a5b33b', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of these is an example of a high-level language?", "options": ["Machine code, since it is the language every computer uses and therefore counts as the highest, most important level", "Python", "Binary", "Assembly language, since its mnemonics are written using letters instead of numbers"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Python is a high-level, English-like language. Machine code, binary and assembly language are all low-level."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:mcq:780e97d6', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of these is the ONLY language a CPU can execute directly?", "options": ["Assembly language, because its mnemonics are designed to be executed by the CPU''s circuits without any further changes", "Machine code", "A high-level language such as Python, once it has simply been saved and closed by the programmer", "Pseudocode, because it is designed to describe an algorithm in a form very close to real program code"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Only machine code (binary) can be executed directly by a CPU. Assembly and high-level languages must first be translated into machine code."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:mcq:37b8432d', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "What is a mnemonic, in the context of assembly language?", "options": ["A long string of binary digits that represents a single machine-code instruction for one type of processor", "A short abbreviation, such as ADD or LDA, that represents one machine-code instruction", "A high-level keyword, such as if or while, that a compiler translates into several machine-code instructions", "A comment written into the source code purely to help other programmers understand what the code is doing"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "A mnemonic is a short abbreviation (like ADD, LDA, STA) used in assembly language, each one representing a single machine-code instruction."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:mcq:16dece41', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of these is a reason a programmer might choose a low-level language over a high-level one?", "options": ["Low-level languages are always quicker for a programmer to write and are far easier to read and debug", "It allows fast, memory-efficient code and direct control of the hardware", "Low-level languages are portable, so the same code will run unchanged on any type of processor", "A low-level language automatically translates itself into machine code without needing any separate translator"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Low-level languages give fast, memory-efficient code and direct hardware control — useful for things like device drivers. They are harder to write and debug, and are not portable."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:mcq:6382ad5e', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Why does a program written in a high-level language need to be translated before it runs?", "options": ["Translation is only needed to make the program''s file size smaller so that it takes up less storage space", "Because a CPU can only execute machine code, not high-level source code", "Translation makes the source code impossible for anyone else to read or copy without permission", "A program does not actually need to be translated at all if it is written carefully enough by the programmer"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "A CPU can only run machine code, so high-level (and assembly) source code must always be translated into machine code first."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:mcq:eb03db31', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which statement about a COMPILER is correct?", "options": ["It translates and runs one statement at a time, stopping the moment it reaches the first error", "It translates the whole program at once, producing a separate executable file", "It must be present on the user''s computer every time the finished program is run", "It cannot report more than one error at a time, no matter how many exist in the source code"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "A compiler translates the entire program in one go, producing an executable file that can then run without the compiler present."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:mcq:4e0b32f8', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which statement about an INTERPRETER is correct?", "options": ["It produces a separate executable file that can be run later without the interpreter being present", "It translates and runs the program one statement at a time", "It reports every error in the whole program together, only after translating all of it", "It always produces a program that runs faster than one produced by a compiler"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "An interpreter translates and runs a program one statement at a time — it does not produce a separate executable, and it stops at the first error rather than reporting them all together."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:mcq:28edf3b5', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A finished, compiled program needs to run as fast as possible for the end user, who does not have any programming software installed. Which translator best suits this?", "options": ["An interpreter, because the end user''s computer will translate each statement freshly and correctly every time it runs", "A compiler", "Neither a compiler nor an interpreter, because a finished program does not need to be translated once it works", "Both a compiler and an interpreter, used one immediately after the other, translating the program twice for safety"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "A compiler produces a standalone executable that runs fast and does not require any translator to be installed on the user''s computer."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:mcq:b9477126', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A student is still writing a new program and wants to find and fix errors as early as possible, one at a time. Which translator is most helpful at this stage?", "options": ["A compiler, because compiling reports every error in the whole program together only once it has fully finished", "An interpreter", "Neither, because errors can only be found by carefully reading through the code without using any translator", "A compiler, because only a compiler is capable of finding errors in a program at all"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "An interpreter stops at the very first error, which suits finding and fixing problems one at a time while a program is being developed."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:mcq:3453f640', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of these correctly describes machine code?", "options": ["A set of short, easy-to-remember abbreviations such as ADD and STA that stand for individual instructions", "Binary instructions that a CPU can execute directly", "An English-like language that a compiler translates into an executable file for the user", "A language that is portable and will run unchanged on any type of processor"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Machine code is written in binary and is the only language a CPU executes directly. Mnemonics describe assembly language, not machine code."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:mcq:20531914', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of these correctly describes assembly language?", "options": ["A set of English-like keywords, such as if and while, that must be compiled before a CPU can run them", "Short mnemonics with a one-to-one relationship with machine-code instructions", "A language that is portable between different types of processor because it is not written in binary", "The only language that a CPU is able to execute directly, without any further translation at all"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Assembly language uses short mnemonics (like ADD, LDA), each one corresponding one-to-one with a single machine-code instruction. It is still specific to one processor type."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:mcq:0bcce7b5', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "One line of a high-level language, such as Python, is usually equivalent to:", "options": ["Exactly one machine-code instruction, because each keyword maps onto a single instruction the CPU can run", "Many machine-code instructions", "No machine-code instructions at all, since the CPU is able to run high-level lines of code directly", "One assembly-language mnemonic, which is then translated into a full machine-code instruction"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "A single high-level statement usually translates into several machine-code instructions — part of what makes high-level languages quicker to write with."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:tf:9a6b9cbd', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A high-level language is easier for humans to read and write than machine code."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — high-level languages use English-like keywords, which are far easier to read and write than binary machine code."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:tf:8397785b', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Machine code is portable and can run unchanged on any type of processor."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Machine code is specific to one type of processor — it is NOT portable. High-level languages are the ones that are portable."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:tf:3c4d2806', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Assembly language mnemonics have a one-to-one relationship with machine-code instructions."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — each assembly mnemonic (like ADD or LDA) corresponds to exactly one machine-code instruction."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:tf:2e89dd68', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A CPU can execute a high-level language''s source code directly, without any translation."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "A CPU can only execute machine code. High-level source code must always be translated into machine code first."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:tf:7dd3e77e', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A compiler translates a program one statement at a time as it runs."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "That describes an interpreter. A compiler translates the WHOLE program at once, before it runs, producing an executable file."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:tf:28dcaf01', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Once a program has been compiled, the compiler does not need to be present for the executable to run."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — compiling only needs to happen once; the resulting executable file can then be run on its own."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:tf:1f6812b3', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "An interpreter stops at the first error it meets, rather than continuing to translate and run the rest of the program."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Correct — this is one reason interpreters are useful for testing and debugging line by line."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:tf:34784029', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "An interpreted program generally runs faster than a compiled one, because interpreters translate more efficiently."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "The opposite is generally true — an interpreted program tends to run slower, because each statement is translated afresh every time it runs."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:learn:c3749c1e', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "High-level languages", "reading": "<h4>Written to be read by humans, not by the CPU</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A <strong>high-level language</strong> is written using English-like keywords and structures — such as <code>if</code>, <code>while</code>, <code>print</code> — which makes it much easier for a programmer to read, write and debug than the code the CPU actually runs.</li>\n<li>High-level languages are <strong>portable</strong>: the same source code can usually be translated to run on many different types of processor, because it is not written for one specific processor''s instruction set.</li>\n<li>One line of high-level code is usually equivalent to <strong>many</strong> machine-code instructions, so a small amount of high-level code does a lot of work.</li>\n<li>Examples: <strong>Python</strong>, <strong>Java</strong>, <strong>C#</strong>.</li>\n<li>A high-level program must still be <strong>translated</strong> into machine code before the CPU can run it — the CPU cannot execute high-level source code directly.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "What does it mean to say a high-level language is ''portable''?", "options": ["It means the language''s source code file is small enough to fit onto a portable USB storage device without being compressed", "The same source code can usually be translated to run on many different types of processor", "It means the finished program can be copied and moved between computers without needing to be reinstalled at all", "It means the language is designed to be carried around and taught easily in schools because its keywords are in English"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Portability means the same source code isn''t tied to one type of processor — it can be translated for different machines. It isn''t about file size or physical portability."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:learn:15bb4f7f', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Low-level languages: machine code", "reading": "<h4>Binary — the only language a CPU runs directly</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Machine code</strong> is written entirely in <strong>binary</strong> (0s and 1s). It is the <strong>only</strong> language a CPU can execute directly, without any further translation.</li>\n<li>Machine code is <strong>specific to one type of processor</strong> — its instruction set — so machine code written for one processor will not run on a different type of processor.</li>\n<li>Machine code is extremely hard for a human to read, write or debug: even a simple task can take many long strings of binary instructions.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">10110000 01100001\n00000100 00000101</div>\n<ul><li>Because it is so low-level, code like this gives a programmer <strong>direct control</strong> over exactly what the hardware does — but at the cost of being very difficult to work with.</li></ul>", "question": "Why is machine code the only language a CPU can run directly?", "options": ["Because machine code files are always much smaller in size than any high-level language''s source code file", "Because machine code is written in binary, and binary is the only form of instruction a CPU''s circuits can execute", "Because machine code was the very first programming language ever to be invented, long before high-level languages existed", "Because machine code always runs faster than a high-level language, no matter which processor it is executed on"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "A CPU''s circuits can only execute binary instructions — that''s what machine code is. High-level and assembly code must be translated into machine code before either can run."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:learn:a110ce6c', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Low-level languages: assembly language", "reading": "<h4>Short mnemonics that map onto machine code</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Assembly language</strong> is the other low-level language. Instead of binary, it uses short <strong>mnemonics</strong> — abbreviations like <code>LOAD</code>, <code>ADD</code>, <code>STA</code> — that are easier for a human to read and write than raw binary.</li>\n<li>Assembly language has a <strong>one-to-one relationship</strong> with machine code: each assembly instruction corresponds to exactly one machine-code instruction.</li>\n<li>Like machine code, assembly language is <strong>specific to one type of processor</strong> — it is not portable between different processor types.</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"code-block\">LOAD A, 5\nADD A, 3\nSTORE A, 100</div>\n<ul><li>Assembly is still hard work compared with a high-level language, but far more readable than a page of raw binary.</li></ul>", "question": "What is the relationship between an assembly language instruction and a machine code instruction?", "options": ["Each assembly instruction usually expands into dozens of separate machine-code instructions once it has been translated", "Each assembly instruction has a one-to-one relationship with a single machine-code instruction", "There is no fixed relationship at all, because assembly language is portable between completely different types of processor", "Assembly instructions are written in binary, in exactly the same way that machine-code instructions are written"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Assembly language mnemonics map one-to-one onto machine code instructions. (It''s high-level statements that typically expand into many machine-code instructions.)"}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:learn:b292ad3a', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Choosing high-level vs low-level", "reading": "<h4>Matching the language to the job</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>High-level languages</strong> are usually chosen because they are quicker to write, easier to read and debug, and portable across different types of computer — good for most general-purpose software.</li>\n<li><strong>Low-level languages</strong> (machine code or assembly) are chosen when a programmer needs the fastest possible, most memory-efficient code, or <strong>direct control of the hardware</strong> — for example, writing a device driver, an operating system kernel, or code for a small embedded system with very little memory.</li>\n<li>The trade-off: low-level code can be faster and smaller, but it takes much longer to write, is far harder to debug, and is tied to one processor type.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A programmer is writing a device driver that must run as fast as possible and control hardware directly. Which type of language is most suitable?", "options": ["A high-level language, because high-level languages always produce the fastest-running code on any processor they are used with", "A low-level language, because it allows fast, memory-efficient code and direct control of the hardware", "It does not matter which type of language is used, because a translator will always fix the resulting speed and memory issues", "A high-level language, because low-level languages cannot be used to control hardware directly at all"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Low-level languages allow fast, memory-efficient code and direct hardware control, which is exactly what a device driver needs."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:learn:ddda1ffc', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Why every program needs a translator", "reading": "<h4>The CPU only understands machine code</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A CPU can only fetch, decode and execute instructions written in <strong>machine code (binary)</strong>. It cannot run high-level source code, and it cannot run assembly language mnemonics, directly.</li>\n<li>This means any program written in a high-level language — or in assembly language — must be <strong>translated into machine code</strong> before it can actually run on a computer.</li>\n<li>This translation is done by a piece of software called a <strong>translator</strong>. For high-level languages, the two main kinds of translator are the <strong>compiler</strong> and the <strong>interpreter</strong>.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Why must a program written in a high-level language be translated before it can run?", "options": ["Because translating a program is the only way to make its source code shorter and therefore quicker to read", "Because a CPU can only execute machine code, and high-level source code is not written in machine code", "Because high-level languages are not allowed to be executed by law, so translation is a legal requirement", "Because translation is optional, and a program will run at the same speed whether it is translated or not"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "A CPU only executes machine code (binary), so any high-level (or assembly) source code has to be translated into machine code first."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:learn:671300cc', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Compilers", "reading": "<h4>Translates the whole program before it runs</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A <strong>compiler</strong> takes the whole source code and translates it, all at once, into machine code — producing a separate <strong>executable file</strong>.</li>\n<li>This translation only needs to happen <strong>once</strong>. After that, the executable file can be run directly, as many times as needed, <strong>without the compiler being present</strong>.</li>\n<li>Because it is already machine code, a compiled program generally <strong>runs fast</strong>.</li>\n<li>If there are errors in the source code, the compiler reports them <strong>all together</strong>, after it has finished compiling — rather than stopping part-way through.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Once a program has been compiled into an executable file, what does the user need to run it?", "options": ["The compiler must still be installed and running every single time the executable file is opened and used", "Nothing but the executable file itself — the compiler does not need to be present to run it", "The original, uncompiled source code file must also be present alongside the executable file at all times", "An interpreter must be installed to translate the executable file into machine code before each run"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "A compiler only needs to translate the program once. The resulting executable file can then be run on its own, without the compiler present."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:learn:5f79f459', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Interpreters", "reading": "<h4>Translates and runs one statement at a time</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>An <strong>interpreter</strong> translates and <strong>runs</strong> a program <strong>one statement at a time</strong>, rather than translating the whole thing first.</li>\n<li>No separate executable file is produced. This means the <strong>interpreter must be present every time</strong> the program is run.</li>\n<li>Because each statement has to be translated freshly every time it runs, an interpreted program is generally <strong>slower</strong> to run than a compiled one.</li>\n<li>An interpreter <strong>stops at the very first error</strong> it meets, rather than carrying on. This makes it good for <strong>testing and debugging</strong> a program line by line, as the programmer finds out immediately where a problem is.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "What happens when an interpreter meets an error while it is translating and running a program?", "options": ["It skips over that one line completely and quietly carries on translating and running the rest of the program", "It stops at the first error it meets, rather than continuing to translate and run the rest of the program", "It automatically fixes the error itself and continues, without telling the programmer what was wrong", "It produces a separate executable file that contains only the lines of the program that ran successfully"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "An interpreter stops at the first error it meets — useful for debugging line by line, since the programmer finds out immediately where the problem is."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:learn:2e882387', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Compiler vs interpreter: choosing between them", "reading": "<h4>Weighing up the benefits and drawbacks</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Compiler</strong> — benefit: the finished executable runs fast and doesn''t need the compiler present. Drawback: errors aren''t seen until the whole program has been compiled.</li>\n<li><strong>Interpreter</strong> — benefit: great for testing/debugging, since it stops right where the first error is. Drawback: it runs more slowly (translating happens every time), and the interpreter must always be present.</li>\n<li><strong>Exam tip</strong>: \"compare compiler and interpreter\" questions want <strong>both</strong> sides — how each one translates, whether it needs to be present, how it handles errors, and how fast the finished program runs.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A programmer is still writing and testing a new program, making frequent small changes. Which type of translator best suits this stage, and why?", "options": ["A compiler, because compiling the whole program again after every single small change is the quickest way to test each change", "An interpreter, because it stops at the first error, which helps the programmer find and fix problems while testing", "Neither type of translator is needed at all while a program is still being written and is not yet finished", "A compiler, because only a compiler is able to produce any error messages when something in the code is wrong"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "An interpreter stops at the first error, which suits frequent testing while a program is being developed. A compiler only reports errors after compiling the whole thing."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:misc:982e1911', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking assembly language IS machine code.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Assembly language and machine code are both <strong>low-level</strong> languages, but they are not the same thing. Machine code is <strong>binary</strong>; assembly language uses <strong>mnemonics</strong> (like ADD, LDA) that still need to be translated, one-to-one, into machine code.</p>", "question": "What is the difference between assembly language and machine code?", "options": ["There is no real difference between them; assembly language and machine code are simply two different names for exactly the same thing", "Assembly language uses mnemonics that still need translating one-to-one into binary machine-code instructions", "Assembly language is a high-level language, whereas machine code is the only low-level language that exists", "Machine code is portable between processors, whereas assembly language is specific to one type of processor only"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Assembly language (mnemonics like ADD, LDA) and machine code (binary) are both low-level, but assembly still has to be translated one-to-one into machine code before a CPU can run it."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:misc:43e59117', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking a compiled program still needs the compiler present to run.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Once a program has been <strong>compiled</strong>, the compiler has already done its job — translating the whole program into a standalone <strong>executable file</strong>. The compiler does <strong>not</strong> need to be present again for that executable to run. (It''s an <strong>interpreter</strong> that must be present every time.)</p>", "question": "Does a user need the original compiler installed to run an already-compiled program?", "options": ["Yes, because the compiler has to translate the same program again from scratch every single time it is run", "No — the executable file produced by the compiler can run on its own, without the compiler present", "Yes, because every executable file secretly contains a full working copy of the compiler inside it", "It depends only on how large the original source code file was before it was compiled by the programmer"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "A compiler only translates the program once, producing a standalone executable. It is an interpreter, not a compiler, that must be present every time the program runs."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:misc:f3bc1675', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking an interpreter produces a separate executable file, just like a compiler does.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> An interpreter does <strong>not</strong> produce a separate file. It translates and <strong>runs</strong> the program one statement at a time, directly — which is why the <strong>interpreter itself must be present every time</strong> the program is run.</p>", "question": "Does an interpreter produce a separate executable file the way a compiler does?", "options": ["Yes, an interpreter always produces exactly the same kind of standalone executable file that a compiler would produce", "No — an interpreter translates and runs the program one statement at a time, without producing an executable file", "Yes, but only for programs that are written in a low-level language rather than a high-level one", "It depends only on which operating system the interpreter itself happens to be installed on at the time"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Unlike a compiler, an interpreter does not create a standalone executable — it translates and runs the source code one statement at a time, so it must be present every time the program is run."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:misc:7a2896a7', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking low-level languages are always the ''better'' choice because they run faster.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Low-level languages can produce fast, memory-efficient code, but they take much <strong>longer to write</strong>, are far <strong>harder to debug</strong>, and are <strong>tied to one processor type</strong>. For most general software, a high-level language''s readability and portability outweigh the speed of low-level code.</p>", "question": "Why might a programmer choose a HIGH-level language even though a low-level language could run faster?", "options": ["Because a high-level language always produces code that runs exactly as fast as a low-level language would", "Because high-level code is quicker to write, easier to debug and portable across different processors", "Because low-level languages are not able to be translated into machine code at all under any circumstances", "Because high-level languages do not need a translator, unlike low-level languages, which always need one"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "High-level languages trade some raw speed for being quicker to write, easier to debug, and portable — usually the better trade-off unless direct hardware control or maximum speed/memory efficiency is essential."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:misc:06289f24', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking ''translator'' only means ''compiler''.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> A <strong>translator</strong> is the general term for software that converts source code into machine code. A <strong>compiler</strong> and an <strong>interpreter</strong> are both types of translator — they just work in different ways.</p>", "question": "Is a compiler the only kind of translator?", "options": ["Yes, a compiler is the only piece of software that is ever able to translate source code into machine code", "No — an interpreter is also a type of translator, working differently from a compiler", "No, because a translator is a type of high-level language rather than a piece of translating software", "Yes, because an interpreter only ever translates assembly language and is unable to translate anything else"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Translator is the general term; compiler and interpreter are the two main types of translator used for high-level languages."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:misc:002dd176', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Thinking an interpreter reports every error together, like a compiler does.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> An interpreter <strong>stops at the very first error</strong> it meets while running the program, rather than carrying on to find every error. It''s a <strong>compiler</strong> that reports all of its errors together, once it has finished compiling the whole program.</p>", "question": "Which translator reports every error in the program together, all at once?", "options": ["An interpreter, because it always finishes translating and running the whole program before reporting anything at all", "A compiler, because it translates the whole program before reporting any errors it has found", "Neither a compiler nor an interpreter is able to report more than one single error under any circumstances", "Both a compiler and an interpreter always report every error together in exactly the same way as each other"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "A compiler translates the whole program first, so it can report all the errors it found together. An interpreter stops at the very first error instead."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:tips:3a25400c', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Compare compiler and interpreter — cover BOTH sides", "reading": "<p>\"Compare a compiler and an interpreter\" is a very common higher-tariff question. Structure your answer around the same three or four points for each translator, so nothing is missed:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>How it translates</strong> — whole program at once (compiler) vs one statement at a time (interpreter).</li>\n<li><strong>What it produces</strong> — a separate executable file (compiler) vs nothing separate; runs directly (interpreter).</li>\n<li><strong>Whether it''s needed to run the program</strong> — compiler not needed after compiling; interpreter needed every time.</li>\n<li><strong>How it handles errors, and speed</strong> — compiler reports errors together and the finished program runs fast; interpreter stops at the first error and each run is generally slower.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>A one-line answer like \"a compiler is faster\" will not score highly — you need the <strong>comparison</strong>, not just a fact about one of them.</p>", "question": "A student answers ''Compare a compiler and an interpreter'' by writing only ''A compiler translates the whole program at once.'' What is missing?", "options": ["Nothing — that single sentence is a complete and sufficient answer to a compare question worth several marks", "A comparison with how an interpreter works, since the question asks for both translators to be compared", "The exact binary machine code that the compiler would produce for a simple example program", "A list of every high-level programming language that could be compiled using that particular compiler"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "A compare question needs both sides — the answer only describes the compiler and says nothing about how an interpreter works, so it can''t score full marks."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:tips:bd897719', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "explain — Why does a program need translating at all?", "reading": "<p>\"Explain why a translator is needed\" questions are really asking you to link two facts together, not just state one of them:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Fact 1: a <strong>CPU can only execute machine code</strong> (binary).</li>\n<li>Fact 2: a high-level (or assembly) program is <strong>not written in machine code</strong>.</li>\n<li>Conclusion: so it must be <strong>translated into machine code</strong> before the CPU is able to run it.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Just writing \"so the computer can understand it\" is too vague to score well — name what a CPU actually runs (machine code), and say what has to happen to the source code before it can.</p>", "question": "Which explanation of ''why a translator is needed'' would score full marks?", "options": ["A translator is needed so the computer can understand the program, in some general and unspecified way", "A CPU can only execute machine code, so high-level source code must be translated into it first", "A translator is needed because programmers find it more convenient to write code in English rather than numbers", "A translator is needed only for very long programs; short programs do not need to be translated at all"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "A full-marks explanation names what the CPU can run (machine code), says the source code isn''t already machine code, and links the two — that''s why translation is needed."}'::jsonb),
('computer-science:2-5-1-languages:tips:fa424885', 'computer-science', 'computer-science:2-5-1-languages', '2.5.1 Languages', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "tip — Justifying a high-level vs low-level choice", "reading": "<p>When a question gives you a scenario and asks you to justify choosing a high-level or a low-level language, link your answer directly to what the scenario needs — don''t just repeat a general definition.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Scenario mentions <strong>speed, memory limits, or direct hardware control</strong> (e.g. a device driver, an embedded sensor) → justify <strong>low-level</strong>.</li>\n<li>Scenario mentions <strong>readability, quick development, or running on different computers</strong> (e.g. a general app, a school project) → justify <strong>high-level</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Example:</strong> \"A high-level language should be used here because the software needs to be written quickly and maintained by several programmers, and it does not need to run on one specific type of processor.\"</p>", "question": "A question describes software that must control a robot''s motor with extremely precise timing and use very little memory. Which justification best fits?", "options": ["A high-level language, because high-level languages are always the easiest choice to justify in any given scenario", "A low-level language, because it allows direct control of the hardware and can be written to be memory-efficient", "Either type of language works equally well here, because the scenario does not actually favour one over the other", "A high-level language, because portability is the most important factor whenever hardware timing is involved"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Precise hardware timing and very limited memory point towards a low-level language, which allows direct hardware control and memory-efficient code."}'::jsonb),
